&lt;p class="MsoNormal"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 9pt; font-family: Tahoma;" lang="EN-GB"&gt;&amp;nbsp;The
explosion took place in the NP buffer tank that is part of the neutralization
section. In this section, adding ammonia neutralizes the acidic liquor from the
previous section in the production process. The ammonia flow is controlled by
an online automatic pH measurement, which is located at the 25 % level of the
tank. In addition, ammonium nitrate is added to obtain the correct ratio
between N and P in the final product. The NP buffer tank is the last unit before
the liquor is pumped to the evaporation and prilling section for making the
final product prills. The NP buffer tank has no instrumented safety functions,
but a high temperature alarm on 145 degrees Celcius is installed. In addition
there is a high and low alarm on the automatic pH measurement an a high alarm
on the online chlorine analyzer. The off gas from the tank is connected to the
recovery system for ammonia.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

